# unittest Guidance

## Project Context

- Test path: {{ test_path | default("tests") }}
- Runner: {{ test_runner | default("python -m unittest or project command") }}
- Async tests: {{ async_tests | default("detected by Akira") }}

## TestCase Shape

- Group tests by class when they share setup around the same subject.
- Name methods `test_<behavior>` with the expected result in the name.
- Keep each test focused on one observable behavior.
- Use the most specific assertion helper available.
- Prefer `setUp()` and `tearDown()` only for genuinely shared setup.
- Use `subTest()` for small input variations inside one behavior.
- Keep helper methods private and local to the test class when possible.

## Assertions

- Use `assertEqual`, `assertIsNone`, `assertRaises`, and related helpers instead
  of generic truthiness checks.
- Assert user-visible behavior and side effects.
- For exception paths, verify the exception type and message when helpful.

{% if async_tests | default(false) %}
## Async Tests

- Use `IsolatedAsyncioTestCase` for async test methods.
- Keep async resource cleanup explicit.
{% endif %}

{% include "_partials/error_handling.md.j2" %}

## Test Data

- Build fresh data per test unless shared immutable fixtures are clearer.
- Keep filesystem and environment changes cleaned up in `tearDown()`.

## Avoid

- Large inheritance trees for test setup.
- Hidden shared mutable state between tests.
- Network calls or machine-specific paths.
- Overusing mocks where a small real object is clearer.
